xamines songs, artworks, advertisements, memes, literature, jokes, and networks that refuse exceptionalist and exoticizing visions of Cuba. Expanding postsocialist critical theory to read this complex mediascape, Duong argues that a materialist critique of Cuba’s revolutionary legacy must account for Cubans’ everyday demands for agency and self-representation. This long overdue reassessment of Cuba’s place in Latin American and post-Marxist studies shows Cuban postsocialism to be an urgent and indispensable referent for core debates on the politics of participatory cultures in new media studies. Portable Postsocialisms performs the crucial task of redefining how we envision imaginaries of social change in Latin America and the Caribbean.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnti-globalization movementxHistoryy21st century. 0aCapitalism and mass mediazCubaxHistoryy21st century. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszCubaxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocial changezCubaxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocialismxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocialismzCubaxHistoryy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aCuba, Cuban culture, Postsocialist Cultures, Post-Marxism, Cuban Literature.  aDigital Culture, Latin American Culture, Caribbean Culture, Latin American Cultural Studies.  aLatin American Media Studies, Cultural Anthropology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32826240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477328279423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477328279/original  a978-3-11-079783-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles